IRS990.Desc: Project 1: Ohana (family) Gardens program continued free to Hawaiian urban families and several area residents (participates self-monitor access to grow edibles). Minimal renovation to key structures provided additional use areas. Continued the pilot products of eggs, ulu, bananas, limes, pomegranates and dragon fruit in anticipation of a new land lease and expanding. Completed a master land plan with Townscape LLC. Released 219 butterflies and expanded the pollinator garden. Hosted Troop 101 (boy scouts) for service projects Firebreaks maintained with support from WCCC volunteers.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: Project 2: Completed a Kaulunani Urban and Community Forestry grant (a program of the DLNR Division of Forestry and Wildlife; and State and Private Forestry, branch of the USDA Forest Service, Region 5). Renewed agreement with Chaminade University to manage the water quality assessment and use of the preserve as an outdoor classroom. Maintained the endangered wetland bird (Hawaiian Moorhen) count of 14 with 2 successful nesting seasons. Extended the self-managed volunteer program (included online tutorial and support) to increase community exposure and opportunity. Planted 25 new native seedlings.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: Other programs, including commencement with seeking access through BWS property to Paiko Ridge. Protected over 300 acres through an acquisition process.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Part II-B, Line 1i - Other Activities Description
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Letters / testimony were sent to Honolulu City Council, Clean Water and Natural Land Commission (CWNL), and Board of Water Supply regarding the East Honolulu Sustainable Communities Plan (two), in support of another nonprofit organization's application for CWNL funds (one), regarding preservation of clean water and the Navy's responsibility related to fuel contamination at Red Hill (one), and one letter related to our Kaiwi property. Request to support the CWNL funding was also sent to members of the community via email.These issues were discussed with the councilmember of District 4.Letters and testimony were written by volunteers, who spent approximately seven hours on lobbying.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Part II, Line 9: Organization Reporting of conservation easements.
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: In 2017 the Hui received a security deposit to be held in perpetuity for any potential litigation or enforcement violations that the Hui may need to pay should the property owner not comply with the easement agreement. Expenses for monitoring the easement in 2022 were approximately $400 and included review of correspondence, newsletters, public minutes, site visits, reporting, phone calls, emails, social media review and internal Hui Board discussions. A third party was engaged to perform this service, and the expense is recorded as part of outside services and printing.On February 14, 2014, the Hui granted a conservation easement to the City and County of Honolulu for its property known as Hawea heiau complex and Keawawa wetland. The agreement includes certain prohibitions and restrictions (unless an exception is expressly provided) as follows: Certain activities normally allowed on Preservation-2 land, e.g., game preserves, recreation facilities, etc.); Subdivision of the land; Dwellings; Commercial activities; Entrance fees; and Uses and activities inconsistent with the purpose of the easement.
OTHER PROGRAM SERVICES 4: Other programs, including commencement with seeking access through BWS property to Paiko Ridge. Protected over 300 acres through an acquisition process.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Two executive board officers (Treasure and President) review a draft of the return. Any corrections are sent to the tax preparer. The return is filed upon approval from the Treasurer or President and shared with the full Board.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 12c
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: A contact list that includes board members' outside affiliations is circulated annually and updated. Board members are expected to disclose conflicts as issues are discussed. The board then decides how to handle the particular conflict.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Part III, Program description Ka Iwi
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Project 3: Ka Iwi Explorations 2022 hosted over 235 residents on educated hikes about the cultural and natural significance of the area. This free community event runs for two days with support from partners The Trust for Public Land, Sierra Club Oahu Group, Maunalua.Net, Kamehameha Schools, State of Hawaii Dept. of Parks & Rec., Hui Nalu and Hawaii Trail and Mountain Club. Completed a flora and fauna report. Opened the lands to UH Manoa archeological professor and students to do field work. Kaiwi mauka trail maintenance and self-managed walk/hike pilot programs extended through the year to assist the public with outdoor opportunities.
